strategy: Always buy the newest if only two choices.  If it turns out too bad to live with, then it's easy to sell and maybe even for a profit.
metastrategy: Just buy the newest house.  It's easier to sell if you don't like it, easier to make a profit

strategy: I checked AC/Heating and the kitchen quality first. If there was a clear winner on both counts, I would go with that. strategy: I didn't personally care about a lot of the features listed, so I ignored those. House size is irrelevant to me. I can be comfortable in tiny or large living spaces, I don't care that much about the yard, don't care about the schools, or anything like that. However, traffic was a major--and often the deciding factor. If the house had terrible traffic, I would not choose it at all, regardless of all other features. If traffic was low and moderate, my next factor would be the quality of thw kitchen. If there wasn't too extreme a difference there, I'd move next to AC quality, and then to yard size. Usually by that point, there was at least one "bad" quality to one of those features. I would then pick the house that had the most overall "alright" qualities to me in all four categories.
metastrategy: I used the same strategy with every house selection, so it was easy to answer the questions in section. I had a very clear idea of how I went about things.
meditation_exp3: 2-4 times per week,5-15 minutes per day,5+ years
attention_check: I will complete this study with my full attention.
permission: Yes, I am okay with my answers to these questions
feedback: No comments. Everything was easy to understand.

strategy:
First and foremost, I look at the evaluation of the nearest school. Usually, they had one that was good and one that was bad. In the case where one was good and one moderate, I looked at distance to nearest park and/or yard-size. 

The items that didn't have much weight in my decisions were condition of kitchen, light, ac/heating unit, size of house, traffic, and distance to local shops and eateries and lastly, distance to nearest public transit. I find that these are all things that can be worked around.
metastrategy:
Based on the examples given about what feature(s) people put emphasis on and what weight (equal) or some more than others that feature vs other features.

I would say that all-in-all I made ever choice beginning with school reputation and unless neither was bad, it was pretty simple from there. It was only with either not being rated bad that I really delve into other features like distance to local parks and sometimes that tied into size of yard.
meditation_exp3: Daily or almost daily,>30 minutes per day,1-3 years

The other factors such as the traffic, amount of light and the nearest school were the least important to me.

If this factor was bad or very bad then I would almost always pick the other choice even if the kitchen( the second most important factor)was bad.  SO the most weight was given to one feature and so it was not necessarily the degree but if it was bad in any way then I went with the other choice.

strategy:
Basically, I only looked at three metrics: AC, Kitchen, and square footage. Square footage tended to be the ultimate decider. If a house was very bad in the AC and Kitchen categories but was 500+ more square footage than the alternative, the size won out (I figure I can adapt to bad AC or kitchen but not to feeling claustrophobic). However if a 700 square foot house had a very good kitchen and AC and was pitted against an alternative with 90 square feet and a "very bad" rating for my other criteria, I would probably choose the smaller space. I only did this when the square footage difference was 400 or lower (but I don't think I decided this exact equation until about a third of the way through).

All things being equal, I think I would rather deal with a "very bad" AC and a good kitchen than the other way around. Not sure how consistent I was with this metric though.
metastrategy:
I don't really understand this question but I'll try...

I knew almost immediately from past rental experiences that ample square footage, a good kitchen, and a functioning AC are three things that most improve my quality of life. I'm fond of parks, natural light, quiet, and a lack of traffic but I feel I can adapt to any deviations in those variables. So my choice process became based on a triangulation of relative values where square footage, AC, and kitchen were concerned.
meditation_exp3: Less than once per week,5-15 minutes per day,5+ years

She cared about each of those two features equally. To decide which home was better overall, she compared how much better each home was on those two features.
binwts_comp2_description: Person description: When making her choices between homes in Section 2, Monica cared about four features: the size of the home, the size of the yard, the amount of traffic, and the amount of noise pollution. She cared about the size of the home and yard the most, but she also cared a little about the other two features.
binatts_comp1_description: Person description: When making his choices between homes in Section 1, Joe cared about three features: the year the building was built, the closeness to public transportation, and the size of the yard. He considered the difference between the two homes on each feature (e.g. a 100 sq. ft. yard versus a 400 sq. ft. yard = a 300 sq. ft. difference), and then weighed those differences together
binatts_comp2_description: Person description: When making his choices between homes in Section 1, Xavier cared about three features: the size of the home, the amount of natural light, and the closeness to cafes/restaurants. He assigned each home a point if it 'won' on that feature (i.e. if it was better on that feature), and then counted up the points and chose the home with the most points.
strategy: The first thing I considered was whether the house had a good heat/ac system. I can deal with sacrificing a lot but I would prefer not to sacrifice that if I can avoid it. Then I looked into the quality of the kitchen. Ideally, I'd like for both of those to be good but if I had to, I sacrificed the quality of the kitchen. Public transportation being close was preferable but it wasn't a deal breaker. Schools wasn't important for me since I don't have kids. The size of the house wasn't too important but when it fit my criteria I preferred the bigger spaces. Yard size wasn't important. I tried to look for little traffic when I could but for some situations it was unavoidable. Parks and cafes weren't super important but the closer the better. I basically looked for my top deal breakers and then made my decisions accordingly based on that.
metastrategy: Since I took the time to apply the same strategy to the majority of the trials, I knew confidently what my decision process was like for this study. Answering the questions in Section 2 was not difficult.

strategy: I went for necessity first, as humans have to modulate their own temperature. And being a rental home, one cannot work on this feature themselves, because it wouldn't be our responsibility and we wouldn't gain any ability to keep the AC as we moved on. It is a health and safety issue. Two, I compared to features of where I rent now and where we just bought a home. Square footage-wise at 1,028 can seem cramped, and if rented areas are dysfunctional or non-usable or being worked on, you get much less usable space. The time periods, like a mid-century home, an older home, pretty new in the 2000s, or 60s to 80s were compared as well. I have experiences with all of them, and they greatly influenced my perceptions of what's feasible and also what types of neighborhoods they were in. The information provided on the table also helped me see if this was something I could figure out what the setting was really matching to. Also the yard space and kitchen were directional, because my partner wants to go outside, as well do I. The kitchen is pain or less pain, it would be rare to find a good rented kitchen, I believe, in general. I've only seen one after trying to find a right space to rent in a 11 years of looking. So if it was said as very good, that could really make a difference. It's just one section at least of a house has to be functioning, and the more sections like in the table, the more they can integrate and enhance each other. The one we currently rent is none except location. Landlords do not do anything for people generally, because they have a mass of power.

You have to have an idea and cannot walk blindly during this process. I also knew the inhumanity of no AC. I mean if you're not able to build shade or systems to modulate for yourself, because someone else has used their position to submit other people into renting, it's really a quality of life reduction and enforcement.

strategy: I tried to concentrate on the couple of traits that were the most important to me first. Then, I tentatively chose the better option. But then I would go through the other traits that were important, even though they weren't as important as the first few, and I would see if any of them were so far against what I wanted. If some of the other traits were so far against what I would want, then I had to go back through all of the traits and decide which I could sacrifice. For example, if the home was really small compared to the other option, I normally would not choose it. But if the smaller option had much less noise pollution and the large option had a really bad kitchen and no natural light, I would sacrifice the larger size in order to have more of the positive traits that I am looking for.
metastrategy: I felt confident when answering the questions in section 2 because I kept a very steady strategy throughout section 1. I knew that the way that I went about choosing each option in section 1 was very similar, if not the same, and I felt very clear about the way that I broke down each decision in my head before making a final choice. So when you asked how I made the decisions, I felt it was very easy to relay to you how I went about choosing each time because it was the same thought process each time.

strategy: I was most interested how good or bad the school system for each home. In my eyes, if the school system is terrible, there's typically something not so great about the area around the school as well. After looking at that, the size of the home was important to me. I typically don't want a home that is under 900 square feet, but will choose if I feel forced. After that, I looked at the size of the yard, as larger yards are typically better for me. However, when forced, I chose homes in a bad school area if the other two things were below what I want. I can put in an alarm system. If a home is a bit smaller than I would like, I can add onto it. If a kitchen is problem, no worries, I can upgrade it, etc.
metastrategy: There were things that I didn't care about if they were bad because I knew that I could fix them. However, you can't do all that much about being in a better area (with a  better school), unless you send your child to a private school, which is expensive. So that was important to me. Also, you can put in an alarm system, but if the area is bad, it's not super safe for your child to play outside without bringin about possible trouble. I chose home size next, because it's easier to choose something that is large enough, and if that's not possible, you can add an addition to your home. Yard was my next interest, but if the first two choices were good or bad, I then made my choice to lose the yard if the first two things were good
